Description of all UMS RFC commands
***********************************

   This section contains the description of all UMS RFC commands and
their command line options. The following syntax will be used:

             -a          Mandantory command line option. You may not omit this
                         option when using a command.
     
             -b <...>    Command line option with parameter. The space between
                         the option and the parameter is optional.
     
             [-c <...>]  Optional command line option. You may omit this option
                         when using a command. The default value will be used
                         instead.

   The commands usually return 0 on success and 20 on error. Exceptions
to this rule will be mentioned in the description for the tool.

   The following UMS RFC commands are available:


Commands for NNTP:

 @{" umsnntp " Link "umsnntp"}           NNTP exporter
 @{" umsnntpd " Link "umsnntpd"}          NNTP importer (server daemon)
 @{" umsnntpget " Link "umsnntpget"}        NNTP importer
 @{" setnntpdate " Link "setnntpdate"}       Set date of the last NNTP access

Commands for POP3:

 @{" umspop3 " Link "umspop3"}           POP3 importer
 @{" umspop3d " Link "umspop3d"}          POP3 exporter (server daemon)

Commands for SMTP:

 @{" umssmtp " Link "umssmtp"}           SMTP exporter
 @{" umssmtpd " Link "umssmtpd"}          SMTP importer (server daemon)

Commands for UUCP:

 @{" ums2uucp " Link "ums2uucp"}          UUCP exporter
 @{" uuxqt " Link "uuxqt"}             UUCP importer

Tools:

 @{" umsrfcprint " Link "umsrfcprint"}       Print UMS messages as RFC messages
 @{" umsrfcwrite " Link "umsrfcwrite"}       Import RFC messages as UMS messages

Common command line options:

 @{" UMS options " Link "UMS options"}       Common UMS related command line options
 @{" Protocol options " Link "Protocol options"}  Common protocol related command line options


@EndNode

@Node "umsnntp" "umsrfc.guide/umsnntp"
@Next "umsnntpd"
@Toc "Commands"

NNTP exporter
=============

   The command @{b}umsnntp@{ub} exports news messages via @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"} to a remote host.

     Syntax:
     
             umsnntp  -h <remote host>
                     [-S <Service name or port number>]
     
                     [-p <UMS password>]
                     [-s <UMS message base>]
                     [-u <UMS user name>]
     
                     [-n <authentication name>]
                     [-i <authentication password>]
     
                     [-b <select bit>]
                     [-I]
     
                     [-c]
                     [-r <n>]
                     [-w <n>]
     
     Defaults:
     
                      -S  Service @{b}nntp@{ub} (port 119)
                      -p  No password
                      -s  Default message base
                      -u  User @{b}NNTP@{ub}
                      -n  jduser
                      -i  secret
                      -b  No select bit
                      -r  360
                      -w  60

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}-n@{ub}
     This name is send to the remote server if it requests user
     authentication. Note that the name is send in clear text!

@{b}-i@{ub}
     This string is send to the remote server if the user
     authentication also requires a password. Note that the password is
     send in clear text!

@{b}-b@{ub}
     Bit number of an additional select bit. Only messages with this
     bit set in the user flags will be exported. This can be used to
     run a special filter program before exporting with @{b}umsnntp@{ub}.

@{b}-I@{ub}
     Use the @{b}IHAVE@{ub} command to send the news messages to the remote
     host. If you don't specify this option, then the @{b}POST@{ub} command is
     used. Most @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"} servers don't allow the @{b}IHAVE@{ub} command for clients,
     so you may not be able to use this option.

@{b}-c@{ub}
     Export news messages continously. After exporting all new messages
     @{b}umsnntp@{ub} will wait a short while and then will start to export all
     new messages which arrived in the meantime.

@{b}-r@{ub}
     Causes @{b}umsnntp@{ub} to rescan the whole message base for new messages
     after @{i}n@{ui} export runs. All messages which couldn't be sent until now
     will be sent again. This option is only useful in conjunction with
     @{b}-c@{ub}.

@{b}-w@{ub}
     Causes @{b}umsnntp@{ub} to wait @{i}n@{ui} seconds between two export runs.  This
     option is only useful inconjunction with @{b}-c@{ub}.

   See also @{"UMS options" Link "UMS options"} and @{"Protocol options" Link "Protocol options"}.


@EndNode

