@Next "umsnntpget"
@Prev "umsnntp"
@Toc "Commands"

NNTP importer (server daemon)
=============================

   The command @{b}umsnntpd@{ub} is a server daemon which offers a transfer
service for news messages via @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"} to remote clients. It can only be
executed by the Internet Super Daemon @{"Inetd" Link "Inetd"}.

     Syntax:
     
             umsnntpd [<UMS user name>]
                      [<UMS password>]
                      [<UMS message base>]
     
     Defaults:
     
                      User @{b}NNTPD@{ub}
                      No password
                      Default message base


@EndNode

@Node "umsnntpget" "umsrfc.guide/umsnntpget"
@Next "setnntpdate"
@Prev "umsnntpd"
@Toc "Commands"

NNTP importer
=============

   The command @{b}umsnntpget@{ub} imports news messages via @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"} from a remote
host.

     Syntax:
     
             umsnntpget  -h <remote host>
                        [-S <Service name or port number>]
     
                        [-p <UMS password>]
                        [-s <UMS message base>]
                        [-u <UMS user name>]
     
                        [-n <authentication name>]
                        [-i <authentication password>]
     
                        [-g]
                        [-P <n>]
                        [-c]
                        [-q]
     
     Defaults:
     
                         -S  Service @{b}nntp@{ub} (port 119)
                         -p  No password
                         -s  Default message base
                         -u  User @{b}NNTP@{ub}
                         -n  jduser
                         -i  secret
                         -P  1

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}-n@{ub}
     This name is send to the remote server if it requests user
     authentication. Note that the name is send in clear text!

@{b}-i@{ub}
     This string is send to the remote server if the user
     authentication also requires a password. Note that the password is
     send in clear text!

@{b}-g@{ub}
     Use the commands @{b}GROUP@{ub}, @{b}STAT@{ub} and @{b}NEXT@{ub} to scan for new news
     messages. This may lower the load on the remote @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"} server but
     the transfer overhead may be significantely higher, especially if
     the server uses long expiration periods for news messages. If you
     don't specify this option the command @{b}NEWNEWS@{ub} is used which only
     transfers information about new messages (see @{"setnntpdate" Link "setnntpdate"}).

@{b}-P@{ub}
     Use @{i}n@{ui} (up to 20) parallel processes to transfer news messages. This
     is useful to make the transfer of news messages over a slow serial
     link more efficient by using most of the available bandwidth.

@{b}-c@{ub}
     Use parameters on the command line after the last valid command
     line option as input parameters. You may request news messages by
     message ID:

          umsnntpget -h nntphost -c 1234@dummy.do.main 6789@test.foo.bar

     or by group names:

          umsnntpget -h nntphost -c -g comp.sys.amiga.misc comp.sys.amiga.datacomm

@{b}-q@{ub}
     Don't print message ids.

   See also @{"nntpget.groups" Link "nntpget.groups"}, @{"UMS options" Link "UMS options"} and @{"Protocol options" Link "Protocol options"}.


@EndNode

@Node "setnntpdate" "umsrfc.guide/setnntpdate"
@Next "umspop3"
@Prev "umsnntpget"
@Toc "Commands"

Set date of the last NNTP access
================================

   The command @{b}setnntpdate@{ub} sets the date of the last @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"} access for
@{"umsnntpget" Link "umsnntpget"}.

     Syntax:
     
             setnntpdate  <UMS user name>
                          <UMS password>
                         [<UMS message base>]
                         [DATE <date string>]
     
     Defaults:
     
                          Default message base

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}DATE@{ub}
     You have to specify the date as defined in RFC 822. @{b}setnntpdate@{ub}
     will transform it to the format which is needed for @{"umsnntpget" Link "umsnntpget"}. If
     you don't specify this option the last access date will be printed
     in RFC 822 format.

   Example:

     setnntpdate NNTP secret DATE "18 Nov 1994 20:05:30"


@EndNode

@Node "umspop3" "umsrfc.guide/umspop3"
@Next "umspop3d"
@Prev "setnntpdate"
@Toc "Commands"

POP3 importer
=============

   The command @{b}umspop3@{ub} imports mail messages via @{"POP3" Link "POP3"} from a remote
host.

     Syntax:
     
             umspop3  -h <remote host>
                     [-S <Service name or port number>]
     
                     [-p <UMS password>]
                     [-s <UMS message base>]
                     [-u <UMS user name>]
     
                      -n <mailbox name>
                      -i <mailbox password>
                     [-k]
     
                     [-c]
                     [-w <n>]
     
     Defaults:
     
                      -S  Service @{b}pop3@{ub} (port 110)
                      -p  No password
                      -s  Default message base
                      -u  User @{b}POP3@{ub}
                      -w  60

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}-n@{ub}
     Name of the mailbox on the remote host.

@{b}-i@{ub}
     Password for the mailbox on the remote host.

@{b}-k@{ub}
     If this option is used @{b}umspop3@{ub} won't delete the messages in the
     mailbox on the remote host. Note that these messages will show up
     as dupes next time you use @{b}umspop3@{ub}!

@{b}-c@{ub}
     Import mail messages continously. After importing all new messages
     @{b}umspop3@{ub} will wait a short while and then will start to import all
     new messages which arrived in the meantime.

@{b}-w@{ub}
     Causes @{b}umspop3@{ub} to wait @{i}n@{ui} seconds between two export runs.  This
     option is only useful inconjunction with @{b}-c@{ub}.

   @{b}umspop3@{ub} returns 5 if there were no messages in the mailbox.

   See also @{"UMS options" Link "UMS options"} and @{"Protocol options" Link "Protocol options"}.


@EndNode

