SMTP exporter
=============

   The command @{b}umssmtp@{ub} exports mail messages via @{"SMTP" Link "SMTP"} to a remote host.

     Syntax:
     
             umssmtp  -h <remote host>
                     [-S <Service name or port number>]
     
                     [-p <UMS password>]
                     [-s <UMS message base>]
                     [-u <UMS user name>]
     
                     [-b <select bit>]
     
                     [-c]
                     [-r <n>]
                     [-w <n>]
     
     Defaults:
     
                      -S  Service @{b}smtp@{ub} (port 25)
                      -p  No password
                      -s  Default message base
                      -u  User @{b}SMTP@{ub}
                      -b  No select bit
                      -r  360
                      -w  60

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}-b@{ub}
     Bit number of an additional select bit. Only messages with this
     bit set in the user flags will be exported. This can be used to
     run a special filter program before exporting with @{b}umssmtp@{ub}.

@{b}-c@{ub}
     Export mail messages continously. After exporting all new messages
     @{b}umssmtp@{ub} will wait a short time and then will start to export all
     new messages which arrived in the meantime.

@{b}-r@{ub}
     Causes @{b}umssmtp@{ub} to rescan the whole message base for new messages
     after @{i}n@{ui} export runs. All messages which couldn't be sent until now
     will be sent again. This option is only useful in conjunction with
     @{b}-c@{ub}.

@{b}-w@{ub}
     Causes @{b}umssmtp@{ub} to wait @{i}n@{ui} seconds between two export runs.  This
     option is only useful inconjunction with @{b}-c@{ub}.

   See also @{"UMS options" Link "UMS options"} and @{"Protocol options" Link "Protocol options"}.

   When @{b}umssmtp@{ub} connects to a @{"SMTP" Link "SMTP"} server it tries to use @{"ESMTP" Link "SMTP"} first.
If this succeeds then @{b}umssmtp@{ub} controls its actions according to the
options offered by the server:

@{b}SIZE@{ub}
     It will tell the server how big the messages are before
     transferring them.

@{b}8BITMIME@{ub}
     It will tell the server which encoding type the message body has
     before transferring it.

@{b}PIPELINING@{ub}
     Commands and responses will be queued to improve performance.


@EndNode

