Print UMS messages as RFC messages
==================================

   The command @{b}umsrfcprint@{ub} prints @{"UMS" Link "UMS"} messages as @{"RFC" Link "RFC"} messages to the
standard output. You can use the output redirection (@{b}>file@{ub}) to write
messages into a file. The printed messages will @{i}not@{ui} be marked as read.
This tool is very helpful when you want to know how the exported message
will look like.

     Syntax:
     
             umsrfcprint  <UMS user name>
                          <UMS password>
                         [<UMS message base>]
                          MSGNUM <n>
                         [DOTS]
     
     Defaults:
     
                          Default message base
                          Don't encode lines beginning with a dot

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}MSGNUM@{ub}
     Specifies which @{"UMS" Link "UMS"} message should be printed.

@{b}DOTS@{ub}
     Some protocols like @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"}, @{"POP3" Link "POP3"} and @{"SMTP" Link "SMTP"} require a special encoding
     of lines beginning with a "." (dot). With this option you can
     enable this encoding.

   Example:

     umsrfcprint >message.txt exporter secret MSGNUM 1234 DOTS


@EndNode

@Node "umsrfcwrite" "umsrfc.guide/umsrfcwrite"
@Next "UMS options"
@Prev "umsrfcprint"
@Toc "Commands"

Import RFC messages as UMS messages
===================================

   The command @{b}umsrfcwrite@{ub} reads @{"RFC" Link "RFC"} messages and imports them as @{"UMS" Link "UMS"}
messages. You can use the input redirection (@{b}<file@{ub}) or the @{b}FILE@{ub}
parameter to read messages from a file. This tool is very helpful when
you want to import messages from other RFC tools.

     Syntax:
     
             umsrfcwrite  <UMS user name>
                          <UMS password>
                         [<UMS message base>]
                         [FILE <filename>]
                         [DOTS]
                         [<recipient1> ...]
     
     Defaults:
     
                          Default message base
                          Read message from standard input
                          Don't decode lines beginning with a dot
                          Import news message

   Explanation of the command line options:

@{b}FILE@{ub}
     Specifies from which file the @{"RFC" Link "RFC"} message should be read instead
     from the standard input.

@{b}DOTS@{ub}
     Some protocols like @{"NNTP" Link "NNTP"}, @{"POP3" Link "POP3"} and @{"SMTP" Link "SMTP"} require a special decoding
     of lines beginning with a "." (dot). With this option you can
     enable this decoding. Note that the last line containing only a
     single dot must have been removed already!

   If you don't specify any recipient addresses then the message will
be imported as news message. If you specify one or more addresses the
message will imported as mail message with the addresses as recipients.

   Note that @{b}umsrfcwrite@{ub} does @{i}not@{ui} transform the @{b}CR-LF@{ub} combination to
@{b}LF@{ub}. Thus you have to perform this transformation yourself before
importing the message with this tool!

   Examples:

     umsrfcwrite importer secret FILE mail.txt DOTS jduser@dummy.test.com
     umsrfcwrite <news.txt importer secret


@EndNode

