@Node "UUCPDirectories" "umsrfc.guide/UUCPDirectories"
@Next "UUCPConfig"
@Prev "Services"
@Toc "Examples"

UUCP directories
================

@{"UUCP" Link "UUCP"} needs three directories for its work:

@{b}Spool directory@{ub}
     Directory for command, data and log files. You should assign
     @{b}UUSPOOL:@{ub} to this directory. Each remote site has its own
     subdirectory. In each subdirectory there should be a directory
     @{b}bad-jobs@{ub} for errorneous jobs. Example with two remote systems
     named @{b}dummy@{ub} and @{b}test@{ub}:

          1> Dir UUSPOOL: all
               dummy (dir)
                    bad-jobs (dir)
               test (dir)
                    bad-jobs (dir)
            logfile                          TimeLog
            XferStat

@{b}Configuration directory@{ub}
     UUCP configuration file reside here. You should assign @{b}UULIB:@{ub} to
     this directory.

          1> Dir UULIB:
            config                           L.Ports
            L.Sys                            security
            seq

@{b}Public directory@{ub}
     Download and upload area for UUCP. You should assign @{b}UUPUB:@{ub} to this
     directory.


@EndNode

@Node "UUCPConfig" "umsrfc.guide/UUCPConfig"
@Next "L.Ports"
@Prev "UUCPDirectories"
@Toc "Examples"

Main UUCP configuration
=======================

   The file @{b}UULIB:config@{ub} contains the @{"UUCP" Link "UUCP"} configuration. A minimal
configuration only needs your node name, a dummy user name and a
setting for the debug level:

     NodeName    foobar
     UserName    root
     Debug       0


@EndNode

@Node "L.Ports" "umsrfc.guide/L.Ports"
@Next "L.Sys"
@Prev "UUCPConfig"
@Toc "Examples"

UUCP ports description
======================

   The file @{b}UULIB:L.Ports@{ub} describes the devices which @{b}uucico@{ub} uses to
contact remote systems. Normally this is a serial port with a modem, so
the file should look like this:

     acu=ser device=serial.device unit=0

   If you want to use @{"UUCP" Link "UUCP"} over @{"TCP-IP" Link "TCP-IP"} you must add another device to
this file:

     acu=tcp device=telser.device unit=0


@EndNode

@Node "L.Sys" "umsrfc.guide/L.Sys"
@Next "UUCPPoll"
@Prev "L.Ports"
@Toc "Examples"

Remote UUCP Systems
===================

   The file @{b}UULIB:L.Sys@{ub} describes how @{b}uucico@{ub} can contact remote
systems. This includes the device to use, the serial line speed, the
phone number and the login script:

     dummy    Any   ser   19200    ATDP123456  ogin: foobar ssword: hello

   To contact a remote system with @{"UUCP" Link "UUCP"} over @{"TCP-IP" Link "TCP-IP"} you replace the
phone number with the hostname of the remote system. So the line should
look like this:

     dummy    Any   tcp   19200    dummy    ogin: foobar ssword: hello


@EndNode

@Node "UUCPPoll" "umsrfc.guide/UUCPPoll"
@Next "Telser"
@Prev "L.Sys"
@Toc "Examples"

UUCP poll script
================

   The following script first exports all messages to the remote system
and then contacts it. You can specify the name of the remote system as
parameter:

     .KEY SYSTEM
     .DEF SYSTEM dummy
     .BRA {
     .KET }
     
     ums2uucp -h {SYSTEM}
     uucico -s{SYSTEM}


@EndNode

